{
  "doc_id": "53567",
  "text": "Latencies between perception and possible motor behavior occur in human beings [CITATION_1] as well. Such discrepancies are caused by neural transmission delays and are constantly compensated by predictive mechanisms in our sensorimotor system that account for both motor prediction and anticipation of the target movement. Miall et al. [CITATION_2] proposed that the human cerebellum is capable of estimating the effects of a motor command through an internal action simulation and a prediction model. Furthermore, there are additional mechanisms for visual motion extrapolation which account for the anticipation of the future position and movement of the target [CITATION_3] . Not only do we predict sensorimotor events in our everyday tasks but we also constantly adjust our delay compensation mechanisms to the sensory feedback [CITATION_4] and to the specific task [CITATION_5] .",
